{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505199"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:27:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:27:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2415"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2415"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.29,0.25,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100449"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2415"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82858"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10727"},{"type":"tags","id":"11198"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2673"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16352"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32656"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100449"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man is brought to the emergency department by his friend due to myoclonic epilepsy. His friend reports that the patient has had several similar episodes before. Episodes are usually triggered by startle. The patient has also complained in the past about muscle weakness. After treating the patient acutely, the doctor asks for consent and performs a muscle biopsy which reveals ragged red fibres. Based on this, a diagnosis of myoclonic epilepsy with ragged red fibres syndrome (MERRF syndrome) is made, which follows mitochondrial inheritance. The patient\u0027s family history is unknown since he was adopted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What is the chance that the patient will pass on this condition to one of his offspring?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0%","25%","50%","75%","100%"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMyoclonic epilepsy with ragged red fibres syndrome (MERRF syndrome) is a hereditary disease and one of the mitochondrial myopathies. Mitochondrial myopathies are passed down to the next generations through mitochondrial DNA. Since sperm contribute no cytoplasm to the zygote (and mitochondria are present in the cytoplasm), the inheritance of mitochondrial myopathies is via the maternal line. This patient likely got the disease from his mother. Since he is a male, there is a \u003Cstrong\u003E0%\u003C/strong\u003E chance of him transferring his condition to one of his offspring.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E25% is incorrect since the patient is a male and cannot pass down a mitochondrial DNA genetic mutation to his offspring.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E50% is incorrect since the patient is a male and cannot pass down a mitochondrial DNA genetic mutation to his offspring. 50% of the offspring may be affected if the offspring have one parent with X-linked dominant disorder.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E75% is incorrect since the patient is a male and cannot pass down a mitochondrial DNA genetic mutation to his offspring.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E100% of the offspring are affected if the mother has a mitochondrial inheritance disorder. This patient himself had a 100% chance of getting this mitochondrial myopathy. However, his offspring will have 0% chance of inheriting the disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["MERRF is caused by pathogenic variants in mtDNA and is transmitted by maternal inheritance"],"references":["Giles RE, Blanc H, Cann HM, Wallace DC. Maternal inheritance of human mitochondrial DNA. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 1980 Nov;77(11):6715-9. doi: 10.1073/pnas.77.11.6715. PMID: 6256757; PMCID: PMC350359."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82858"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2415"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82858"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-25T19:00:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-25T19:01:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2415"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100449"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":nu